CHANGELOG = [
    "b436: chroma_key.py despill generalised for any key colour. The old version hard-coded green (cap G at max(R,B)); the new one identifies the key's dominant channels (above the colour's mean) and caps each at the highest weak (below-mean) channel. Reduces to identical behaviour for a green key, and now handles magenta/blue/cyan/etc. cleanly -- unblocks switching the Gemini round-trip to a magenta key, which has zero overlap with the sprite palette and avoids the green-on-green collision that was leaving residual fringe.",
    "b435: widened the sprite despill to 4px (was 2) to reach green anti-aliasing fringe lining deeper concavities and the inside of holes, where the narrower pass couldn't. Confirmed safe against genuinely green art -- slimes, green spell-crosses, green potions and herbs keep their colour, because edge-band despill only neutralises the ring of pixels near transparency and never touches sprite interiors. (Established that residual key-green and real green art are the SAME colour, so no global colour filter can separate them -- the fix has to stay spatial/edge-based.)",
    "b434: scrubbed the faint green edge-fringe off the now-transparent sprites. After the Gemini key, anti-aliased silhouettes still carried a sliver of the key green -- near-invisible on the dark game panels but visible on lighter backdrops. New sprite_package/code/despill_pool.py does a post-hoc edge-band despill straight on the canonical pool: for every RGBA sprite it pulls the green channel down to max(R,B) in the ring of opaque pixels within 2px of transparency, leaving interiors untouched so genuinely green creatures (serpents, dragons, green-skinned mages) keep their colour. Ran over all 1,321 in-game sprites; edges are clean on any background now.",
    "b433: ALL 1,321 in-game sprites now have transparent backgrounds instead of the old stone/grey/vignette boxes -- a big visual upgrade, every weapon, monster, potion, room and character sprite now sits cleanly on whatever's behind it in the room/UI. Done end-to-end through the new Gemini montage pipeline: the whole library was packed into 21 grid sheets (gemini_montage.py pack, 8x8 @ 1024px so Gemini doesn't downscale, bottom-right corner reserved so its watermark lands on nothing), each sheet's background was repainted flat green by Gemini, then sliced back out with edge-band chroma keying + margin-trim framing recovery and folded straight into the canonical pool (slice --dechroma --into-pool). Unlabeled returns were content-matched to their sheets automatically. Pool entries are now RGBA WebP.",
    "b432: gemini_montage.py `slice` gained --into-pool, which writes each keyed transparent sprite straight back into a canonical_pool .pkl -- re-encoding to WebP (quality 80, matching promote_all_sprites) and updating img_b64 only for matching in-game pids, leaving everything else untouched. This lets the de-greened sheets be folded into the SHIPPED pool incrementally, one sheet at a time as they come back from Gemini, instead of waiting for a final bulk promote -- so a long 21-sheet round-trip can be committed in safe checkpoints. Requires --dechroma (the pool needs the transparent result, not the green cells). Verified on a pool copy: 63 entries updated to RGBA, entry count unchanged, a control pid from another sheet left identical.",
    "b431: hardened the Gemini sprite pipeline after a real 12x12 round-trip exposed three issues. (1) Green halos: Gemini downscaled the 1536px sheet to ~1024, blending a fat green ring into every anti-aliased edge that the old despill (which only touched semi-transparent pixels) left behind. chroma_key.py now does EDGE-BAND despill -- full green-spill removal in the ring of kept pixels within --despill-band px (default 3) of transparency -- killing the halo while leaving interiors alone, so genuinely green sprites still survive. numpy-only dilation, no new deps. (2) Watermark: Gemini stamps its logo over the bottom-right sprite, so `pack` gained --reserve-corner N to leave the last N grid cells empty as a logo landing zone (the manifest skips them; sprites shift to later sheets). (3) Framing: a sprite came back smaller-in-frame because of the cell margin, so `slice --dechroma` now trims the known margin fraction and rescales to sprite_size -- a FIXED fraction so relative sizes (ring vs greatsword) are preserved (autocrop-to-content would wrongly balloon every sprite). --no-fit opts out. Verified end-to-end on the greened sheet: 143 clean, framed, halo-free sprites.",
    "b430: gemini_montage.py `slice` gained a --dechroma flag that runs slice + chroma-key in one pass, so the post-Gemini step is a single command (output PNGs are transparent and ready for promote_all_sprites.py). It reuses chroma_key.py's exact keying algorithm via a lazy import (so plain pack/slice still work without numpy), auto-detecting the flat-green key per cell from that cell's margin -- or --key HEX to force it, with the usual --inner/--outer/--no-despill knobs passed through. Verified end-to-end on a synthetic greened return resized to a non-square 1180x1040: all 64 cells came back transparent-margin + opaque-subject and correctly mapped to their pids.",
    "b429: new sprite montage tool (sprite_package/code/gemini_montage.py) to make the Gemini 'repaint the background flat green' round-trip cheap. Shipping 1,300+ sprites one-at-a-time is wasteful (per-image token cost + per-request image limits), so `pack` lays them out into a few grid sheets (default 8x8 = 64 per 1024x1024 sheet; 21 sheets for the whole in-game pool) and writes a manifest.json recording each sprite's row/col; `slice` re-cuts Gemini's returned sheets back into per-pid PNGs for chroma_key + promote. Built for Gemini being a generative model: slice cuts cells by GRID FRACTION (sheet_w/cols), so a resized/rescaled return still maps cell-for-cell -- verified by slicing a deliberately non-square 1180x1040 resize of a 1024 sheet and getting every sprite back in the right place. Each sprite is centred in a green-margin cell so minor misalignment eats throwaway margin (which chroma_key removes) not the sprite; pid->cell mapping lives in the manifest by position, not burned-in text, so Gemini can't corrupt it (--labeled emits a *_ref.png with pids for your eyes). Pulls from --from-pool or a PNG folder. Decision context: tested rembg and deterministic flood-fill as ways to skip Gemini entirely, but both fail silently on this library (vignette/dark-moated backgrounds overlap subject tones) -- Gemini's flat-green normalisation is what makes the chroma key reliable, so the win is making the SHIP cheap, not removing Gemini. Standalone dev tooling; no game-runtime change.",
]

